{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"737155f6-0511-4e92-bda8-464b71a359b8","content":"This repo doesn't contain docs on that topic, but here's the general approach for macOS:\n\n**1. Enable core dumps via the kernel:**\n```bash\nsudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\nsudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\n**2. Check for Apple crash reports:**\nmacOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for `.ips` or `.crash` files named after your process.\n\n**3. Retrieve the core file:**\nAfter reproducing the crash, look in `/cores/` for a file like `core.<PID>`.\n\n**4. Analyze with `lldb`:**\n```bash\nlldb /path/to/your/app --core /cores/core.12345\n```\n\n**Key notes for NativeAOT specifically:**\n- Since `createdump` is a CoreCLR tool and isn't bundled with NativeAOT, you rely entirely on the OS-level mechanisms above.\n- Make sure your app is published with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) or keep the `.dsym` bundle alongside the binary so `lldb` can resolve frames.\n- On recent macOS versions, SIP may interfere with core dump generation for apps in protected directories — test from a user-writable location.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"08a2708d-82e9-463d-b6fe-fb1305c51418","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't contain relevant documentation on this topic. Let me answer from my general knowledge about macOS crash dumps and NativeAOT.","outputTokens":382,"requestId":"942C:239A50:25AA1D:2CE889:69E8201D"},"id":"c6b0a325-0626-4dfd-9921-afe9b93eb02e","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:11:05.129Z","parentId":"57f142d3-67ec-4844-bc90-59d17cc492f5"}
